<p><b>Sugar</b> is a class of edible <a href="/wiki/Crystal" title="Crystal">crystalline</a> substances, mainly <a href="/wiki/Sucrose" title="Sucrose">sucrose</a>, <a href="/wiki/Lactose" title="Lactose">lactose</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Fructose" title="Fructose">fructose</a>. Human <a href="/wiki/Taste_bud" title="Taste bud">taste buds</a> interpret its <a href="/wiki/Flavor" title="Flavor">flavor</a> as <a href="/wiki/Sweet" title="Sweet" class="mw-redirect">sweet</a>. Sugar as a basic <a href="/wiki/Food" title="Food">food</a> <a href="/wiki/Carbohydrate" title="Carbohydrate">carbohydrate</a> primarily comes from <a href="/wiki/Sugar_cane" title="Sugar cane" class="mw-redirect">sugar cane</a> and from <a href="/wiki/Sugar_beet" title="Sugar beet">sugar beet</a>, but also appears in <a href="/wiki/Fruit" title="Fruit">fruit</a>, <a href="/wiki/Honey" title="Honey">honey</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sorghum" title="Sorghum">sorghum</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sugar_maple" title="Sugar maple" class="mw-redirect">sugar maple</a> (in <a href="/wiki/Maple_syrup" title="Maple syrup">maple syrup</a>), and in many other sources. It forms the main ingredient in much <a href="/wiki/Candy" title="Candy">candy</a>. Excessive consumption of sugar has been associated with increased incidences of type 2 <a href="/wiki/Diabetes" title="Diabetes" class="mw-redirect">diabetes</a>, <a href="/wiki/Obesity" title="Obesity">obesity</a> and <a href="/wiki/Tooth_decay" title="Tooth decay" class="mw-redirect">tooth decay</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-webmd_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-webmd-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
